This case has not been concluded. Unless a judgment of conviction is entered, the defendant is presumed innocent of all charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

2:14 PM (64-06) Defendant Charles G Kummerow Jr. appeared by video.  Attorney Larry R Pruden in court for Charles G Kummerow Jr.  Plaintiff State of Wisconsin by ADA Herrmann in court. 
State called to the stand as a witness, Officer Matthew Boney.
Matthew Boney duly sworn by the clerk and testified on direct examination by ADA Herrmann. 
Witness has identified the defendant on the video in court. Exhibit #1, Criminal Complaint and Amended Complaint  marked, identified and discussed.
Attorney Pruden is objecting to the receipt of Exhibits.
Requesting Court take judicial notice of file 19CF571. Objection by Attorney Pruden. Court will take judicial notice of file 19CF571.

Defense requesting dismissal.

Arraignment held in open court.
Attorney Pruden acknowledged receipt of the Information, waived reading and plead not guilty to all charges on behalf of his client.
Speedy Trial reserved.
